com.mesosfer

Class MesosferQuery<T extends MesosferObject>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.mesosfer.MesosferQuery<T>

  • public class MesosferQuery<T extends MesosferObject>
extends Object
    The MesosferQuery class defines a query that is used to fetch MesosferObjects. The most common use case is finding all objects that match a query through the findInBackground() method, using a FindCallback. For example, this sample code fetches all objects of class "MyClass". It calls a different function depending on whether the fetch succeeded or not. 

     MesosferQuery<MesosferObject> query = MesosferQuery.getQuery("MyClass");
 query.findInBackground(new FindCallback<MesosferObject>() {
     public void done(List<MesosferObject> objects, MesosferException e) {
         if (e == null) {
             objectsWereRetrievedSuccessfully(objects);
         } else {
             objectRetrievalFailed();
         }
     }
 }

    A MesosferQuery can also be used to retrieve a single object whose id is known, through the getInBackground(String) method, using a GetCallback. For example, this sample code fetches an object of class "MyClass" and id myId. It calls a different function depending on whether the fetch succeeded or not. 

     MesosferQuery<MesosferObject> query = MesosferQuery.getQuery("MyClass");
 query.getInBackground(myId, new GetCallback<MesosferObject>() {
     public void done(MesosferObject object, MesosferException e) {
         if (e == null) {
             objectWasRetrievedSuccessfully(object);
         } else {
             objectRetrievalFailed();
         }
     }
 }

    A MesosferQuery can also be used to count the number of objects that match the query without retrieving all of those objects. For example, this sample code counts the number of objects of the class "MyClass". 

     MesosferQuery<MesosferObject> query = MesosferQuery.getQuery("MyClass");
 query.countInBackground(new CountCallback() {
     public void done(int count, MesosferException e) {
         if (e == null) {
             objectsWereCounted(count);
         } else {
             objectCountFailed();
         }
     }
 }

    Using the callback methods is usually preferred because the network operation will not block the calling thread. However, in some cases it may be easier to use the find(), get(String) or count() calls, which do block the calling thread. For example, if your application has already spawned a background task to perform work, that background task could use the blocking calls and avoid the code complexity of callbacks.

      • selectKeys

        public MesosferQuery<T> selectKeys(Collection<String> keys)
        Restrict the fields of returned MesosferObjects to only include the provided keys.

        If this is called multiple times, then all of the keys specified in each of the calls will be included.

        Note: This option will be ignored when querying from the local datastore. This is done since all the keys will be in memory anyway and there will be no performance gain from removing them.

        Parameters:
        keys - The set of keys to include in the result.
        Returns:
        this, so you can chain this call.
